<font color="#FF0000">ANTI-WAR MOVEMENT &amp; NORTH VN</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 29 19:48:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Charles:<br><br>
Those that would dare to rise in opposition to the Hanoi government were simply shot and killed. <br><br>
The soldiers were all together a different story. Some South Vietnamese soldiers that had gone North in 1959 did riot when they were treated miserably. They were forcefully put down by the North Vietnamese  Army. <br><br>
When the Vietnam war started, a captured 19 year old NVA private, reported, &quot;I think that only 20% were enthusiastic about going south. The remaining 80 % did not want to go. About 10% of the men boldly returned their personal effects and weapons and asked to go home.... They were indoctrinated and educated... criticized... after some time they agreed to go south.” When they further refused to go, they were forced south. <br><br>
One item of interest that has never been fully explored is the resentment the North Vietnamese soldier had toward South Vietnamese regroupees that had gone North then were among the first to return South. How much they hated them and how the NVA soldier felt superior to the South Vietnamese civilians as well as the local VC.<br><br>
The NVA soldier were also told that the majority of the South Vietnamese people supported their effort and that most of the country was in NVA hands, and that once they launched the Tet offensive, 90% of the South Vietnamese people were ready to help them over throw the South Vietnamese government and its Army.  Of course once they got South they soon learned that it was not true. <br><br>
They were also told that the non-military people in the US were supportive of the revolution they were carrying out. Communist Cadre members and high-ranking officers in Hanoi often bragged about, &quot;winning the war  on the streets of New York and campuses of New England.&quot; <br><br>
I recall that some of the NVA soldiers we found dead after a fire fight had tattoos on their bodies that said in Vietnamese: &quot;Born in the North to die in the South,&quot; or something similar to that.<br><br>
A greater question may be asked if the Anti-war demonstrators and their allies were so successful in stopping the war, where are they today? Who puts Ant-war demonstrator on their resumes and runs for political office.<br>
We now know that the Anti-war movement was very much lead by communist sympathizers and left wing radicals at home, whose secret agenda called for the over throw of the US government.<br><br>
Cook Barela<br><br>
PS Charles an interesting book you may want to read is called,<br>
&quot;Inside the VC and the NVA,&quot; By Michael lee lanning and Dan Cragg, published by Ballantine Books, 1992. It will give you some great insights into the overall North Vietnamese military originization. 
